title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore East (Late Show) on 1970-02-13
description: Set 1 China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Me & My Uncle, Dire Wolf, Smokestack Lightning Set 2 Monkey & The Engineer, Little Sadie, Wake Up Little Susie-> Black Peter, Uncle John's Band, Katie Mae Set 3 Dark Star-> Cryptical Envelopement-> Drums-> The Other One-> Cryptical Envelopement-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: We Bid You Good Night Late show. Though actually all one set, it was played in electric> acoustic> electric segments. Other artist(s): GD: The Allman Brothers Band: Love. This date is featured on Dick's Picks 4.

reviews.review_text:
Show changed me Read where another commenter said he and friends went out in the woods and played this one on a boom box tripping. 
Maybe its the night I was there, doubt it cause do not recognize the name. But that's how this show changed my life. We were young and loving this band. A high school friends cousin was into them big time he brought us some mind bending things from the west coast and we all kicked back and threw this one on. 
 As one can imagine we were full flight by the time the Dark Star > Other One > Lovelight hit us Like a freight train. In the way only this band can hit someone. We would throw our own home made acid tests to this show never did it come together like the 1st time.
 This show can only get 5 stars no less ever.

Uncle John's Band I don't wish to sound ungrateful at all--this is one great site and I thank all contributors, especially Charlie Miller--but I'm partial to this copy over the CM only because Uncle John's Band is complete on this one. It has a pretty great sound, also (granted not nearly as good to my ears as the CM). But this one is still worlds better than just a straight forward aud copy. Great work!

Rolling Stones List Of Top 20 Dead Shows This show is on the list at #7 and worth a listen.

http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/20-essential-grateful-dead-shows-20130408

- A much-overrated show. Far better Dark Stars & Other Ones can be heard from this period. The "Bear's Choice" acoustic songs are nice.

What is the point of talking about “if we didn’t have all these pristine recordings on the archive”? The fact is, we do! If we didn’t, you’d have no chance to utter such sentences.

Let a poor boy RIDE.. ;)
umm, having grown up in N.Y.C I can tell you every night
I always wanted to be in the coolest spot, whether that was hanging in the neighborhood, going to a local party or venturing out to hear some live music. 
It is hard for me to imagine wanting to do anything else besides being at a show like this. (except maybe "Reaching on over my left shoulder")
The older stoners would talk in hushed tones about the good ol days, seeing shows at the Fillmore, Jerry in his prime. Duuuuuuuuuuaannnnnnnne.
Anyhow, i don't know i guess if somebody now has access to more pristine GD thru the Archives then most hippies ever got touring and tape trading --that somehow this might rate under a 5 spot. But seriously--- I freaking doubt it. Catch the feeling groovy jam slinking thru the Dark Star..
Also the taper running commentary adds a great touch.
"Youth is wasted on the young
and a contact high is worse then a project dime bag"
C. Freedom

Top Ten Dark Star > Cryp > OO > Cryp > Lovelight I happen to agree with most of Rolling Stone's 20 essential shows to have.  And this late show is one of those essentials per David Fricke.  It would have been interesting checking out NJPG's other Dark Star's to have from this era... if he had identified them.  Oh well?  Mine are 11/11/73 and 9/21/72 as #1 and #2.  This one et al is definitely in the top ten, also being in agreement with many of the other reviewers. I never have cared for the deep space of later years since screeching and feedback just isn't my thing. And there is none of it here.

But what I find as amazing as the music is the respect (and probably awe) the audience has for the performance. As another reviewer commented (being there that night) in the quietest moments of Dark Star, you could hear a pin drop in the audience. And for that to happen with a rollicksome, frolicsome, drug-crazed New York City crowd - THAT's saying something!

Dick's Pick's #4 is simply gorgeous as a pristine document. I've copied this version for comparison. But DP4 is beyond compare for sound quality...my having to add a little bass and reverb to soften its brightness. Love the NFA tease before The Other One.  Also loved Bear's Choice from the first day I spun it many many moons ago, mixing this and the 14th's acoustic with Reckoning.
